        "text": "Numbers 15:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The essential meaning of the former word is a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "circle",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", hence applied to the cake because of its shape, and of the latter word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "perforation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", hence applied to the cake because it was perforated. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "A good piece of flesh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is the Authorized Version rendering of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֶשְׁפָּר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which occurs only in the parallel place and here. The Vulgate translates ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "assatura bubulae carnis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the Septuagint, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐσχαρίτη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The imagined derivation of the word from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פָּר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (ox) and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֵשׁ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (fire), or from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "שָׁפַד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (to burn), seems to be what has led to these translations, helped, perhaps, by the apparent convenience of adapting ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "meat",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from the sacrifice to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "bread.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " But Gesenius, Rodiger, Keil, and others prefer the derivation ",
